ns and non-Native populations, and the lingering racism and misunderstanding that permeates the national consciousness to this day. “Clearing the Plains is a tour de force that dismantles and destroys the view that Canada has a special claim to humanity in its treatment of indigenous peoples. Daschuk shows how infectious disease and state-supported starvation combined to create a creeping, relentless catastrophe that persists to the present day. The prose is gripping, the analysis is incisive, and the narrative is so chilling that it leaves its reader stunned and disturbed. For days after reading it, I was unable to shake a profound sense of sorrow. This is fearless, evidence-driven history at its finest.” Elizabeth A. Fenn, author of Pox Americana  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanada (Ouest)xColonisationxAspect sanitairexHistoire. 0aCanada (Ouest)xRelations interethniquesxHistoire. 0aCanada, Western-Colonization-Health aspects-History. 0aCanada, Western-Ethnic relations-History. 0aIndians of North AmericaxDiseaseszCanada, WesternxHistory. 0aIndians of North AmericaxHealth and hygienezCanada, WesternxHistory. 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxGovernment relations. 0aIndians of North AmericazCanada, WesternxHistory. 0aIndians of North America-Canada, Western-History. 0aIndians of North America-Canada-Government relations. 0aIndians of North America-Diseases-Canada, Western-History. 0aIndians of North America-Health and hygiene-Canada, Western-History. 0aIndiens d'Amaerique - Canada - Relations avec l'aEtat. 7aHISTORY / Native American.2bisacsh  aAboriginal, Sir John A., population health, starvation policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Packag